	abstract = {Asparagopsis taxiformis, a widely distributed tropical-subtropical red seaweed (Rhodophyta,  order Bonnemaisoniales), is native to the Hawaiian Islands. This species is highly valued as a  food condiment in Hawaiʻi because of its pungent flavor. Asparagopsis taxiformis has high  concentrations of halogenated secondary metabolites with antibacterial and antiviral activity that  may have powerful medicinal value. Although a related species in Portugal, A. armata, is being  successfully grown in tank culture, little is known about the biotic and abiotic conditions needed  by A. taxiformis to progress through each life phase. This project tested culture conditions that  promote growth and reproduction of each life phase of A. taxiformis.  Tetrasporophyte growth was highest at 24 μmol photons m-2 s-1 when cultured in half strength  PES media at 21-23°C, 12L:12D, under cool white fluorescent bulbs. Gametophytes did not  survive in flask culture under any of the conditions tested due to contamination, although  isolation of apical tips using agar was effective in beginning unialgal gametophyte petri dish  culture. Optimal conditions for inducing carpospore release involved immersing fertile female  thalli in filtered seawater in complete darkness for 16 hours, at 21-23°C. Peak spore release  occurred four hours after fluorescent lights came on. Germination rates were similar when  spores were grown in both f/2 and PES media. Analysis of historic spatial and temporal  distribution of herbaria specimens indicated that gametophytes grow on both leeward and  windward coasts of Hawaiʻi, during both wet and dry seasons. Phenological data suggested that  laboratory conditions probably play a bigger role in carpospore release and germination than the  environmental parameters observed in the four weeks antecedent to collection. This research reveals that a unialgal culture of A. taxiformis may be begun from wild-collected gametophyte  thalli, and grown successfully in